<Layout title="Lesson 8: Software & Programming">
  <div class="lesson-header">
    <span class="lesson-badge">Lesson 8</span>
    <h1>Software & Programming</h1>
    <p class="lesson-subtitle">Showcase your team's software engineering and programming efforts.</p>
    <LessonAudio slug="lesson-7" />
  </div>

  <p>
    This lesson covers how to showcase your team's software engineering and programming efforts in your portfolio.
  </p>

  <h2>Why Software Matters</h2>
  <p>
    Many teams focus heavily on mechanical design but underestimate how important software is to judges.
    Your code demonstrates problem-solving, optimization, and engineering rigor, which are all critical skills.
  </p>

  <h2>What to Include</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Software Architecture</strong>: How is your code organized? What design patterns do you use?</li>
    <li><strong>Key Algorithms</strong>: Autonomous routines, control systems, vision processing, etc.</li>
    <li><strong>Unique Implementations</strong>: What makes your code different or better?</li>
    <li><strong>Path Planning</strong>: What libraries or custom code did you use for Uauto path planning?</li>
    <li><strong>Performance Improvements</strong>: How did your software evolve throughout the season?</li>
    <li><strong>Challenges Overcome</strong>: Technical problems and how you solved them</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How to Present Code</h2>
  <p>
    Most judges won't understand your code, so focus on <strong>explaining the concepts</strong> rather than the syntax:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Use diagrams</strong>: Flowcharts showing how your autonomous routine works</li>
    <li><strong>Provide context</strong>: Why did you choose this approach?</li>
    <li><strong>Show results</strong>: How much faster? More accurate? More reliable?</li>
    <li><strong>Keep it simple</strong>: Don't overwhelm with technical terms</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Allocation Guidelines</h2>
  <p>
    Software typically occupies <strong>1-2 pages</strong> of your portfolio. The exact amount depends on:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>How software-focused your strategy is</li>
    <li>The complexity of your autonomous routines</li>
    <li>How much software improved your season performance</li>
    <li>Space available after covering mechanical systems</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="callout note">
    <strong><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" style="display: inline-block; vertical-align: -0.15em; margin-right: 0.25em;"><path d="M11 4H4a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v14a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h14a2 2 0 0 0 2-2v-7"></path><path d="M18.5 2.5a2.121 2.121 0 0 1 3 3L12 15l-4 1 1-4 9.5-9.5z"></path></svg>Remember:</strong> If your team's strength is software, you can allocate more space. If mechanical is your focus, 1 page is sufficient.
    The portfolio should reflect your team's priorities.
